You’re seeing that huge `duration` because LiveKit reports `FileInfo.duration` in **nanoseconds**, but we were treating it as seconds.

I’ve updated `handleEgressEnded` in `supabase/functions/livekit-webhook/index.ts` to convert nanoseconds → seconds once and reuse it everywhere:

```598:683:supabase/functions/livekit-webhook/index.ts
  const file = fileResults?.[0] ?? legacyFile;
  ...
  const bucketName = 'live-review-recordings';
  const recordingUrl = `${bucketName}/${file.filename}`;

  // LiveKit FileInfo.duration is reported in nanoseconds (int64).
  // Convert to whole seconds for storage & display.
  const recordingDurationSeconds = file.duration
    ? Math.floor(Number(file.duration) / 1_000_000_000)
    : 0;

  await supabase
    .from('live_review_sessions')
    .update({
      recording_status: 'ready',
      recording_url: recordingUrl,
      recording_duration_seconds: recordingDurationSeconds,
      recording_file_size: file.size,
    })
    .eq('id', session.id);

  ...
  await supabase
    .from('review_fulfillment_drafts')
    .update({
      review_content: 'Live video review recording',
      draft_data: {
        live_session_id: session.id,
        recording_url: recordingUrl,
        recording_duration_seconds: recordingDurationSeconds,
      },
      last_saved_at: new Date().toISOString(),
    })
    .eq('application_id', session.application_id)
    .select('id')
    .single();

  ...
  await supabase.from('notifications').insert({
    user_id: sessionDetails.requester_id,
    type: 'live_review_recording_ready',
    data: {
      live_review_session_id: session.id,
      request_title: request?.title || 'Live Review',
      business_name: request?.business_name || '',
      application_id: session.application_id,
      request_id: sessionDetails.review_request_id,
      duration: recordingDurationSeconds,
    },
    is_read: false,
  });
```

New egress events will now store and notify using correct **seconds** rather than the raw nanosecond value; existing records won’t be changed retroactively.

**What’s happening**

- That stack trace is coming from our explicit `stopEgress` call in `handleRoomFinished` trying to stop an egress that LiveKit has already completed (`EGRESS_COMPLETE`), which returns `412 failed_precondition`.  
- The error was already caught and logged as a warning, but the log output is noisy.

**Fix I applied**

In `handleRoomFinished`, I made `stopEgress` treat this specific case as benign and log a simple info instead of a scary warning:

```260:278:supabase/functions/livekit-webhook/index.ts
      try {
        const livekitUrl = Deno.env.get('LIVEKIT_URL');
        const livekitApiKey = Deno.env.get('LIVEKIT_API_KEY');
        const livekitApiSecret = Deno.env.get('LIVEKIT_API_SECRET');
        if (livekitUrl && livekitApiKey && livekitApiSecret) {
          const egressClient = new EgressClient(
            livekitUrl,
            livekitApiKey,
            livekitApiSecret,
          );
          await egressClient.stopEgress(session.recording_egress_id);
          console.log(
            `Explicitly stopped egress ${session.recording_egress_id} for session ${session.id}`,
          );
        }
      } catch (stopError) {
        // Egress may already be stopping or complete — handle gracefully.
        const status = (stopError as any)?.status;
        const code = (stopError as any)?.code;
        const message = (stopError as any)?.message ?? '';

        if (
          status === 412 ||
          code === 'failed_precondition' ||
          message.includes('EGRESS_COMPLETE')
        ) {
          console.log(
            `Egress ${session.recording_egress_id} already complete; no need to stop explicitly.`,
          );
        } else {
          console.warn(
            `Failed to stop egress ${session.recording_egress_id}:`,
            stopError,
          );
        }
      }
```

Now when LiveKit returns `failed_precondition` because the egress is already complete, you’ll just see a calm “already complete” log and no alarming error stack, while genuine failures still surface as warnings.

That error is coming from the webhook trying to serialize a `BigInt` in the LiveKit egress payload.

I’ve updated `supabase/functions/livekit-webhook/index.ts` so it now:

- **Stops JSON-stringifying raw egress objects** (which may contain `BigInt`), replacing this:

```571:572:supabase/functions/livekit-webhook/index.ts
console.log(
  `Egress ended for ${roomName}: egressId=${egressId}, fileResults=${JSON.stringify(fileResults)}, legacyFile=${JSON.stringify(legacyFile)}, error=${error}`,
);
```

with a safe log that doesn’t stringify nested values:

```570:575:supabase/functions/livekit-webhook/index.ts
const { roomName, egressId, fileResults, file: legacyFile, error } =
  event.egressInfo;

// Avoid JSON.stringify on raw egress objects since they may contain BigInt.
console.log(
  `Egress ended for ${roomName}: egressId=${egressId}, hasFileResults=${
    Array.isArray(fileResults)
  }, hasLegacyFile=${!!legacyFile}, error=${error}`,
);
```

- **Coerces the file size to a plain `number` before sending it to Supabase**:

```609:625:supabase/functions/livekit-webhook/index.ts
const bucketName = 'live-review-recordings';
const recordingUrl = `${bucketName}/${file.filename}`;

// LiveKit FileInfo.duration is reported in nanoseconds (int64).
// Convert to whole seconds for storage & display.
const recordingDurationSeconds = file.duration
  ? Math.floor(Number(file.duration) / 1_000_000_000)
  : 0;

// FileInfo.size may be a BigInt; coerce to a plain number for JSON serialization.
const recordingFileSize =
  typeof (file as any).size === 'bigint'
    ? Number((file as any).size)
    : Number(file.size ?? 0);

await supabase
  .from('live_review_sessions')
  .update({
    recording_status: 'ready',
    recording_url: recordingUrl,
    recording_duration_seconds: recordingDurationSeconds,
    recording_file_size: recordingFileSize,
  })
  .eq('id', session.id);
```

With these changes, the webhook should no longer throw `TypeError: Do not know how to serialize a BigInt` on egress-ended events.

You’re seeing “object not found” because `recording_url` in `live_review_sessions` included the bucket name, but Supabase Storage expects just the **object path inside the bucket**.

I’ve fixed this in two places:

- **DAL: normalize the path before signing**  
  `getRecordingUrl` now strips the `live-review-recordings/` prefix if present, so it works for both old and new rows:

```871:903:packages/dal/src/services/live-review-service.ts
  async getRecordingUrl(
    sessionId: string,
  ): Promise<ApiResponse<{ url: string; expiresAt: string }>> {
    // First get the session to get the recording path
    const { data: session, error: sessionError } = await this.supabase
      .from('live_review_sessions')
      .select('recording_url, recording_status')
      .eq('id', sessionId)
      .single();
    ...
    if (session.recording_status !== 'ready' || !session.recording_url) {
      return {
        error: {
          message: 'Recording not available',
          code: 'RECORDING_NOT_READY',
        },
      };
    }

    // Normalize recording path: older rows may include bucket prefix, new ones should not.
    const bucket = 'live-review-recordings';
    const objectPath = session.recording_url.startsWith(`${bucket}/`)
      ? session.recording_url.slice(bucket.length + 1)
      : session.recording_url;

    // Generate signed URL
    const { data: signedUrl, error: signError } = await this.supabase.storage
      .from(bucket)
      .createSignedUrl(objectPath, 3600); // 1 hour expiry
```

- **Webhook: store only the object path going forward**  
  `handleEgressEnded` now saves just the filename (no bucket name) into `recording_url`:

```609:625:supabase/functions/livekit-webhook/index.ts
  // Store only the object path (without bucket name). Supabase Storage buckets
  // are configured separately; DAL will add the bucket when generating URLs.
  const recordingPath = file.filename;

  // LiveKit FileInfo.duration is reported in nanoseconds (int64).
  // Convert to whole seconds for storage & display.
  const recordingDurationSeconds = file.duration
    ? Math.floor(Number(file.duration) / 1_000_000_000)
    : 0;

  ...

  await supabase
    .from('live_review_sessions')
    .update({
      recording_status: 'ready',
      recording_url: recordingPath,
      recording_duration_seconds: recordingDurationSeconds,
      recording_file_size: recordingFileSize,
    })
    .eq('id', session.id);
```

With these changes, `LiveVideoFulfillmentViewer`’s `getRecordingUrl` call will correctly sign and return the URL even for existing rows that have `recording_url = "live-review-recordings/.../file.mp4"`.
